(1, 'Corneal Abrasion', '<h2 style=\"text-align: center;\">Corneal Abrasion</h2>\r\n<h3>Overview</h3>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">A corneal abrasion is a scratch or cut (abrasion) of the clear outer layer (cornea) of the eye. Injury (trauma) is the most common cause for corneal abrasions. The most common trauma causes are:<br /><br />1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Scratches from fingernails (human and animal)<br /><br />2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Foreign objects hitting the cornea (eg, dirt, wood splinters, metal shavings, plants, tree branches)<br /><br />3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Curling irons<br /><br />4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Excessive rubbing of the eye<br /><br />5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Overexposure to ultraviolet light<br /><br />6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Arc welding light exposure<br /><br />7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Over wearing of contact lenses<br /><br />8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ill-fitting contact lenses<br /><br />9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Torn contact lenses<br /><br />10&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Makeup brushes<br /><br />11&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Paper cuts<br /><br />12&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Chemical burns<br /><br />13&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Irregular eyelashes rubbing the cornea or falling off into the eye<br /><br />14&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A foreign object that gets caught under the eyelid, which then irritates the cornea each time you blink</p>\r\n<p>Other causes include underlying eye conditions, such as:<br /><br />1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Inability to fully close the eyelids<br /><br />2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Abnormalities of the lid position<br /><br />3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Severe dry eye conditions<br /><br />4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Severe, chronic blepharitis (inflamed eyelids)<br />First Aid Guide<br /><br />Most simple corneal abrasions will heal on their own within a day or two at most. Other things that help include:<br /><br />1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Keeping the eye shut<br /><br />2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Never rubbing the injured eye<br /><br />3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Immediately removing a contact lens &ndash; contact lens wearers should always have a back-up pair of glasses for when contact lenses should not be worn<br /><br />4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Using artificial tears to bathe the eye<br /><br />5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Using clean water to rinse the eye and wash out suspect foreign matter<br /><br />6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Using sunglasses to reduce light sensitivity<br /><br />There are precautions that you can take to prevent getting a corneal abrasion. These include:<br /><br />1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wearing protective eyewear for all conditions that might result in a corneal abrasion, such as working around the garden, working on grinding machines, etc<br /><br />2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Being extra careful when using makeup brushes and curling irons<br /><br />3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Taking excellent care of and using excellent hygiene with contact lenses<br /><br />4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Never sleeping in contact lenses, regardless of manufacture notes</p>', 'uploadimg/66ded66031.jpg');

